  <detection>
    - Implement pinning with backup pins
    - Detect Frida/debugging attempts
    - Check for app modification (signature verification)
    - Monitor for unusual traffic patterns
    - Implement multiple pinning layers
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Successfully intercept pinned traffic
    - Extract API credentials from traffic
    - Document bypass method used
    - Test across app versions
    - Verify persistence of bypass
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - Start with Objection - it handles most common cases automatically
    - For stubborn apps, trace SSL functions with Frida first
    - Network Security Config bypass requires APK modification
    - iOS requires jailbreak or advanced techniques
    - Some apps detect Frida - use frida-gadget stealth
    - Check for multiple pinning implementations (library + custom)
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Certificate pinning is a defense-in-depth measure, not a security boundary. With physical device access or debug capability, it can always be bypassed. For mobile testing, the question is not "can it be bypassed" but "how quickly." Start with the easiest method (Objection) and escalate to binary patching only if needed.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
